<DOC><DOCNO> AP880420-0054 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-88 0446EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-MingoCorruption     04-20 0227</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Mingo Corruption,0233</SECOND><HEAD>Mingo Sheriffs Sentenced For Selling, Buying Job</HEAD><DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two former sheriffs of a mountain coalmining county received prison terms of up to 10 years for a schemein which one sold his job to the other for $100,000.   Former Mingo County Democratic chairman Johnie Owens, who hasadmitted selling his job as sheriff in 1982, sentenced Tuesday toone to five years in prison and fined $20,000 on state charges ofconspiracy and tax evasion.   The sentences will run concurrently with a 14-year sentenceOwens received Monday on related federal charges.   Eddie Hilbert, 45, who has said he gave Owens a $20,000 downpayment for the job, was sentenced Tuesday to one to 10 years inprison for bribery.   Circuit Judge Dan O'Hanlon also placed the two on five years'probation and ordered them to pay as-yet undetermined costs of thespecial grand jury investigation of their case.   Hilbert pleaded guilty to related federal charges Monday and isscheduled for sentencing June 16.   West Virginia law prescribes specific sentences for each crime.Only a parole board can shorten a sentence after a convict servesthe minimum term.   The county, known historically as the site of the Hatfield-McCoyfeud, is at the center of a two-year political corruption and drugtrafficking investigation in which nearly 50 officials have beencharged.</TEXT></DOC>